__cs__ In Kathmandu , I was escorted by women who had previously been sex slaves themselves .
__cs__ They ushered me down a narrow set of stairs that led to this dirty , dimly fluorescent lit basement .
__cs__ This wasn &apos;t a brothel , per se .
__cs__ It was more like a restaurant .
__cs__ Cabin restaurants , as they &apos;re known in the trade , are venues for forced prostitution .
__cs__ Each has small , private rooms , where the slaves , women , along with young girls and boys , some as young as seven years old , are forced to entertain the clients , encouraging them to buy more food and alcohol .
__cs__ Each cubicle is dark and dingy , identified with a painted number on the wall , and partitioned by plywood and a curtain .
__cs__ The workers here often endure tragic sexual abuse at the hands of their customers .
__cs__ Standing in the near darkness , I remember feeling this quick , hot fear , and in that instant , I could only imagine what it must be like to be trapped in that hell .
__cs__ I had only one way out : the stairs from where I &apos;d come in .
__cs__ There were no back doors .
__cs__ There were no windows large enough to climb through .
__cs__ These people have no escape at all , and as we take in such a difficult subject , it &apos;s important to note that slavery , including sex trafficking , occurs in our own backyard as well .
__cs__ Tens of hundreds of people are enslaved in agriculture , in restaurants , in domestic servitude , and the list can go on .
__cs__ Recently , the New York Times reported that between 100,000 and 300,000 American children are sold into sex slavery every year .
__cs__ It &apos;s all around us . We just don &apos;t see it .
__cs__ The textile industry is another one we often think of when we hear about slave labor .
__cs__ I visited villages in India where entire families were enslaved in the silk trade .
__cs__ This is a family portrait .
__cs__ The dyed black hands are the father , while the blue and red hands are his sons .
__cs__ They mix dye in these big barrels , and they submerge the silk into the liquid up to their elbows , but the dye is toxic .
__cs__ My interpreter told me their stories .
__cs__ &quot; &quot; We have no freedom , &quot; &quot; they said .
__cs__ &quot; &quot; We hope still , though , that we could leave this house someday and go someplace else where we actually get paid for our dyeing . &quot; &quot; It &apos;s estimated that more than 4,000 children are enslaved on Lake Volta , the largest man-made lake in the world .
__cs__ When we first arrived , I went to have a quick look .
__cs__ I saw what seemed to be a family fishing on a boat , two older brothers , some younger kids , makes sense right ?
__cs__ Wrong . They were all enslaved .
__cs__ Children are taken from their families and trafficked and vanished , and they &apos;re forced to work endless hours on these boats on the lake , even though they do not know how to swim .
__cs__ This young child is eight years old .
__cs__ He was trembling when our boat approached , frightened it would run over his tiny canoe .
__cs__ He was petrified he would be knocked in the water .
__cs__ The skeletal tree limbs submerged in Lake Volta often catch the fishing nets , and weary , frightened children are thrown into the water to untether the lines .
__cs__ Many of them drown .
__cs__ For as long as he can recall , he &apos;s been forced to work on the lake .
__cs__ Terrified of his master , he will not run away , and since he &apos;s been treated with cruelty all his life , he passes that down to the younger slaves that he manages .
__cs__ I met these boys at five in the morning , when they were hauling in the last of their nets , but they had been working since 1 a.m.
__cs__ in the cold , windy night .
__cs__ And it &apos;s important to note that these nets weigh more than a thousand pounds when they &apos;re full of fish .
__cs__ I want to introduce you to Kofi .
__cs__ Kofi was rescued from a fishing village .
__cs__ I met him at a shelter where Free the Slaves rehabilitates victims of slavery .
__cs__ Here he &apos;s seen taking a bath at the well , pouring big buckets of water over his head , and the wonderful news is , as you and I are sitting here talking today , Kofi has been reunited with his family , and what &apos;s even better , his family has been given tools to make a living and to keep their children safe .
__cs__ Kofi is the embodiment of possibility .
__cs__ Who will he become because someone took a stand and made a difference in his life ?
__cs__ Driving down a road in Ghana with partners of Free the Slaves , a fellow abolitionist on a moped suddenly sped up to our cruiser and tapped on the window .
__cs__ He told us to follow him down a dirt road into the jungle .
__cs__ At the end of the road , he urged us out of the car , and told the driver to quickly leave .
__cs__ Then he pointed toward this barely visible footpath , and said , &quot; &quot; This is the path , this is the path . Go . &quot; &quot; As we started down the path , we pushed aside the vines blocking the way , and after about an hour of walking in , found that the trail had become flooded by recent rains , so I hoisted the photo gear above my head as we descended into these waters up to my chest .
__cs__ After another two hours of hiking , the winding trail abruptly ended at a clearing , and before us was a mass of holes that could fit into the size of a football field , and all of them were full of enslaved people laboring .
__cs__ Many women had children strapped to their backs while they were panning for gold , wading in water poisoned by mercury .
__cs__ Mercury is used in the extraction process .
__cs__ These miners are enslaved in a mine shaft in another part of Ghana .
__cs__ When they came out of the shaft , they were soaking wet from their own sweat .
__cs__ I remember looking into their tired , bloodshot eyes , for many of them had been underground for 72 hours .
__cs__ The shafts are up to 300 feet deep , and they carry out heavy bags of stone that later will be transported to another area , where the stone will be pounded so that they can extract the gold .
__cs__ At first glance , the pounding site seems full of powerful men , but when we look closer , we see some less fortunate working on the fringes , and children too .
__cs__ All of them are victim to injury , illness and violence .
__cs__ In fact , it &apos;s very likely that this muscular person will end up like this one here , racked with tuberculosis and mercury poisoning in just a few years .
__cs__ This is Manuru . When his father died , his uncle trafficked him to work with him in the mines .
__cs__ When his uncle died , Manuru inherited his uncle &apos;s debt , which further forced him into being enslaved in the mines .
__cs__ When I met him , he had been working in the mines for 14 years , and the leg injury that you see here is actually from a mining accident , one so severe doctors say his leg should be amputated .
__cs__ On top of that , Manuru has tuberculosis , yet he &apos;s still forced to work day in and day out in that mine shaft .
__cs__ Even still , he has a dream that he will become free and become educated with the help of local activists like Free the Slaves , and it &apos;s this sort of determination , in the face of unimaginable odds , that fills me with complete awe .
__cs__ I want to shine a light on slavery .
__cs__ When I was working in the field , I brought lots of candles with me , and with the help of my interpreter , I imparted to the people I was photographing that I wanted to illuminate their stories and their plight , so when it was safe for them , and safe for me , I made these images .
__cs__ They knew their image would be seen by you out in the world .
__cs__ I wanted them to know that we will be bearing witness to them , and that we will do whatever we can to help make a difference in their lives .
__cs__ I truly believe , if we can see one another as fellow human beings , then it becomes very difficult to tolerate atrocities like slavery .
__cs__ These images are not of issues . They are of people , real people , like you and me , all deserving of the same rights , dignity and respect in their lives .
__cs__ There is not a day that goes by that I don &apos;t think of these many beautiful , mistreated people I &apos;ve had the tremendous honor of meeting .
__cs__ I hope that these images awaken a force in those who view them , people like you , and I hope that force will ignite a fire , and that fire will shine a light on slavery , for without that light , the beast of bondage can continue to live in the shadows .
__cs__ Thank you very much .
