__cs__ My first grade teacher had this brilliant idea .
__cs__ She wanted us to experience receiving gifts but also learning the virtue of complimenting each other .
__cs__ So she had all of us come to the front of the classroom , and she bought all of us gifts and stacked them in the corner .
__cs__ And she said , &quot; &quot; Why don &apos;t we just stand here and compliment each other ?
__cs__ If you hear your name called , go and pick up your gift and sit down . &quot; &quot; What a wonderful idea , right ?
__cs__ What could go wrong ?
__cs__ ( Laughter ) Well , there were 40 of us to start with , and every time I heard someone &apos;s name called , I would give out the heartiest cheer .
__cs__ And then there were 20 people left , and 10 people left , and five left ...
__cs__ and three left .
__cs__ And I was one of them .
__cs__ And the compliments stopped .
__cs__ Well , at that moment , I was crying .
__cs__ And the teacher was freaking out .
__cs__ She was like , &quot; &quot; Hey , would anyone say anything nice about these people ? &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) &quot; &quot; No one ? OK , why don &apos;t you go get your gift and sit down .
__cs__ So behave next year — someone might say something nice about you . &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) Well , as I &apos;m describing this you , you probably know I remember this really well . ( Laughter )
__cs__ But I don &apos;t know who felt worse that day .
__cs__ Was it me or the teacher ?
__cs__ She must have realized that she turned a team-building event into a public roast for three six-year-olds .
