__cs__ So that was one version of me , and I would die to avoid being in that situation again — to get rejected in public again .
__cs__ That &apos;s one version .
__cs__ Then fast-forward eight years .
__cs__ Bill Gates came to my hometown — Beijing , China — to speak , and I saw his message .
__cs__ I fell in love with that guy .
__cs__ I thought , wow , I know what I want to do now .
__cs__ That night I wrote a letter to my family telling them : &quot; &quot; By age 25 , I will build the biggest company in the world , and that company will buy Microsoft . &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) I totally embraced this idea of conquering the world — domination , right ?
__cs__ And I didn &apos;t make this up , I did write that letter .
__cs__ And here it is — ( Laughter ) You don &apos;t have to read this through — ( Laughter ) This is also bad handwriting , but I did highlight some key words .
__cs__ ( Laughter ) So ...
__cs__ that was another version of me : one who will conquer the world .
__cs__ Well , then two years later , I was presented with the opportunity to come to the United States .
__cs__ I jumped on it , because that was where Bill Gates lived , right ?
__cs__ ( Laughter ) I thought that was the start of my entrepreneur journey .
__cs__ Then , fast-forward another 14 years .
__cs__ I was 30 .
__cs__ Nope , I didn &apos;t build that company .
__cs__ I didn &apos;t even start .
__cs__ I was actually a marketing manager for a Fortune 500 company .
__cs__ And I felt I was stuck ; I was stagnant .
__cs__ Why is that ?
__cs__ Where is that 14-year-old who wrote that letter ?
__cs__ It &apos;s not because he didn &apos;t try .
__cs__ It &apos;s because every time I had a new idea , every time I wanted to try something new , even at work — I wanted to make a proposal , I wanted to speak up in front of people in a group — I felt there was this constant battle between the 14-year-old and the six-year-old .
__cs__ One wanted to conquer the world — make a difference — another was afraid of rejection .
__cs__ And every time that six-year-old won .
__cs__ And this fear even persisted after I started my own company .
__cs__ I mean , I started my own company when I was 30 — if you want to be Bill Gates , you &apos;ve got to start sooner or later , right ?
__cs__ When I was an entrepreneur , I was presented with an investment opportunity , and then I was turned down .
__cs__ And that rejection hurt me .
__cs__ It hurt me so bad that I wanted to quit right there .
__cs__ But then I thought , hey , would Bill Gates quit after a simple investment rejection ?
__cs__ Would any successful entrepreneur quit like that ?
__cs__ No way .
__cs__ And this is where it clicked for me .
__cs__ OK , I can build a better company .
__cs__ I can build a better team or better product , but one thing for sure : I &apos;ve got to be a better leader .
__cs__ I &apos;ve got to be a better person .
__cs__ I cannot let that six-year-old keep dictating my life anymore .
__cs__ I have to put him back in his place .
__cs__ So this is where I went online and looked for help .
__cs__ Google was my friend .
__cs__ ( Laughter ) I searched , &quot; &quot; How do I overcome the fear of rejection ? &quot; &quot; I came up with a bunch of psychology articles about where the fear and pain are coming from .
__cs__ Then I came up with a bunch of &quot; &quot; rah-rah &quot; &quot; inspirational articles about &quot; &quot; Don &apos;t take it personally , just overcome it . &quot; &quot; Who doesn &apos;t know that ?
__cs__ ( Laughter ) But why was I still so scared ?
__cs__ Then I found this website by luck .
